For years, we've been using media queries to make responsive layouts. But media queries have a fundamental flaw: they respond to the **viewport**, not to the **container** a component lives in.
This means a card component that looks great in a full-width layout breaks when you put it in a sidebar. Container queries fix this.
## The Problem with Media Queries
Consider a card component used in two contexts:
1. A main content area (wide)
2. A sidebar (narrow)
With media queries, you'd write something like:
```css
.card {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;
}

@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .card {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
}
```
But what if the sidebar is 300px wide on a 1200px screen? The media query doesn't fire — the card stays in its wide layout, even though it doesn't have enough space.
<callout icon="💡" color="blue_bg">
	**The core insight:** Components should adapt to *their own available space*, not the viewport width. This is what container queries give us.
</callout>
## How Container Queries Work
Container queries require two things:
1. A **containment context** on the parent
2. A **@container rule** on the child
```css
/* Step 1: Establish containment context */
.card-wrapper {
  container-type: inline-size;
}

/* Step 2: Query the container */
@container (min-width: 400px) {
  .card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;
  }
}

@container (max-width: 399px) {
  .card {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
  }
}
```
Now the card adapts based on how much space its *wrapper* provides — regardless of viewport size.
## Named Containers
When you have nested containers, you can name them to be explicit about which one you're querying:
```css
.sidebar {
  container-type: inline-size;
  container-name: sidebar;
}

.main-content {
  container-type: inline-size;
  container-name: main;
}

/* Target a specific container */
@container sidebar (max-width: 300px) {
  .nav-links {
    flex-direction: column;
  }
}
```
You can also use the shorthand:
```css
.sidebar {
  container: sidebar / inline-size;
}
```
## Practical Example: Responsive Card
Here's a complete card component that works in any context:
```html
<div class="card-container">
  <article class="card">
    <img src="thumbnail.jpg" alt="" class="card-image" />
    <div class="card-body">
      <h3 class="card-title">Article Title</h3>
      <p class="card-text">A brief description of the article...</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</div>
```
```css
.card-container {
  container-type: inline-size;
}

.card {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  border-radius: 8px;
  overflow: hidden;
  box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
}

.card-image {
  width: 100%;
  aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;
  object-fit: cover;
}

/* When the container is wide enough, switch to horizontal layout */
@container (min-width: 500px) {
  .card {
    flex-direction: row;
  }

  .card-image {
    width: 200px;
    aspect-ratio: auto;
  }
}

/* Extra-wide container: add more spacing */
@container (min-width: 700px) {
  .card-body {
    padding: 2rem;
  }

  .card-title {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
  }
}
```
Drop this card into a sidebar, a grid, a modal, or full-width — it just works.
## Container Query Units
Container queries also introduce new units relative to the container's dimensions:
1. `cqw` — 1% of the container's width
2. `cqh` — 1% of the container's height
3. `cqi` — 1% of the container's inline size
4. `cqb` — 1% of the container's block size
```css
.card-title {
  /* Font size scales with container width */
  font-size: clamp(1rem, 3cqi, 1.5rem);
}
```
## Browser Support
Container queries are supported in all modern browsers since February 2023:
- Chrome 105+
- Firefox 110+
- Safari 16+
For older browsers, the media-query-based layout serves as a natural fallback — the `@container` rules simply don't apply.
---
Container queries are a paradigm shift. Instead of building pages that are responsive, we can now build **components** that are responsive. This makes them truly portable and reusable across different layouts without modification.
